# Economy Basics O/X
> Core ideas about money and the economy
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.economy-finance.basic/

Inflation refers to a general rise in prices over time. | O | Inflation means the overall level of prices keeps rising.
When demand rises and supply stays the same, prices usually fall. | X | When demand rises with fixed supply, prices usually rise, not fall.
A central bank can influence interest rates in an economy. | O | Central banks set policy rates that guide interest rates across the economy.
GDP stands for the total population of a country. | X | GDP means Gross Domestic Product, the value of goods and services produced.
Diversifying investments can help reduce risk. | O | Spreading money across assets lowers the impact of any single loss.
A budget deficit means income is greater than spending. | X | A deficit means spending is greater than income.
Banks accept deposits and provide loans. | O | Banks take in deposits and lend money out to borrowers.
Buying a company's stock makes you a creditor who lent it money. | X | Buying stock makes you a shareholder who owns part of the company.
Compound interest means earning interest on both principal and prior interest. | O | With compound interest, earned interest is added and itself earns interest.
Deflation means prices are continuously rising. | X | Deflation means prices are continuously falling; rising prices are inflation.
Supply and demand influence the price of goods. | O | The balance of supply and demand shapes market prices.
Taxes are voluntary donations that citizens may choose not to pay. | X | Taxes are compulsory payments required by law, not voluntary donations.
A recession is a significant, broad decline in economic activity. | O | A recession is a widespread drop in output, income, and employment lasting more than a few months.
When a country's currency gains value, its imports become more expensive. | X | A stronger currency buys more foreign goods, so imports actually become cheaper.
Interest is the cost of borrowing money. | O | Borrowers pay interest as the price of using a lender's money over time.
A bond represents a share of ownership in a company. | X | A bond is a loan to the issuer; stocks, not bonds, represent ownership.
The unemployment rate measures the share of the labor force that is jobless but seeking work. | O | It counts people who are actively looking for a job but do not have one, as a share of the labor force.
Printing more money always makes a country wealthier. | X | Printing money without more goods and services tends to cause inflation, not real wealth.
Opportunity cost is the value of the next best option you give up when making a choice. | O | Every choice means forgoing alternatives; the best forgone alternative is the opportunity cost.
The stock market only ever moves upward and never falls. | X | Stock prices rise and fall; markets regularly experience declines as well as gains.
A monopoly is a market controlled by a single seller. | O | In a monopoly, one seller dominates the market with no close competitors.
Money you deposit at a bank sits locked in a vault and is never lent out. | X | Banks keep only part of deposits on hand and lend the rest out to earn interest.
Exports are goods and services sold to other countries. | O | Exports are what a country sells abroad, while imports are what it buys from abroad.
A higher credit score generally makes it more expensive to borrow money. | X | A higher credit score usually earns lower interest rates, making borrowing cheaper.
Fiscal policy involves government decisions on spending and taxation. | O | Fiscal policy uses government spending and taxes to influence the economy.
Barter requires the use of money to trade goods. | X | Barter is the direct exchange of goods or services without using money.
Scarcity means resources are limited relative to people's wants. | O | Scarcity is the basic economic problem that unlimited wants exceed limited resources.
Inflation increases the purchasing power of money. | X | Inflation raises prices, so each unit of money buys less; its purchasing power falls.
A dividend is a payment made to shareholders out of a company's profits. | O | Companies may distribute part of their earnings to shareholders as dividends.
Gross profit is calculated after subtracting all of a company's operating expenses. | X | Gross profit subtracts only the cost of goods sold; net profit accounts for all expenses.
A supply chain links producers of raw materials through to final consumers. | O | A supply chain is the network of steps that turns raw materials into products delivered to customers.
A progressive tax charges lower earners a higher percentage than higher earners. | X | A progressive tax charges higher earners a higher percentage, not lower earners.
Insurance spreads financial risk across many policyholders. | O | Many people pay premiums so that the few who suffer losses can be compensated, pooling risk.
The law of demand says people buy more of a good as its price rises. | X | The law of demand states that, all else equal, people buy less as the price rises.
Capital refers to assets used to produce goods and services. | O | Capital includes tools, machines, and buildings used in producing goods and services.
A trade surplus means a country imports more than it exports. | X | A trade surplus means exports exceed imports; the opposite is a trade deficit.
